text: Talked about this on Twitter but just for the sake of a more private venue, there was a section of a meeting at my job where someone got up and told a story about how they struggled with depression and nearly committed suicide and how they got help and it didn't end their career but just hearing someone struggle with things I sometime struggle with freaking destroyed me emotionally today and I don't know what to do now.
Hits close to home man. It's rough
Pretty much. Hearing things like "I struggled with thoughts like XYZ" and I'm sitting there running the meeting like "Way to fucking break my soul first thing in the morning, thanks"
I understand some of where you're coming from. I've been there. If you need to talk about it I'm here
I really need to go to mental health. I'm in the service, it's free, I really have no excuses except my own personal problems
going to therapy was probably the best thing I ever did for myself
I mean, if your kids were feeling what you were feeling right now, what would you want them to do
get help, right?
show them the right thing to do

If you have access, take advantage. There are tons of people who don't have that same type of opportunity. The lack of mental health facilities (or rather the inability to deal with high volume) has been a massive debate at my college for the last two years.

I know this thinking is wrong, I constantly tell myself it is, but I can never get past the idea that I just fucking hate the idea of being told "Yeah, there's something wrong with you, you're broken." I know that's not what anyone would say or mean, but that's all I can think about when calling for help. I barely talk to Dani about stuff. It's taken 10 years of being together to get to the point where I can AT MOST tell her "I'm depressed today" instead of just "I'm fine, just tired"
for sure
You're able to tell us. Is a therapist scarier than telling us?
I've always had an easier time typing or writing than speaking
there is a service for that
It's a reason I tell people that I'm probably going to be weird at events meeting me in person for the first time
If it helps, and this is what I did when I was seeing a therapist, take some notes ahead of time.
though it might not work with the army stuffs
You can even just hand them to your therapist and as them to use them as talking points.
It's easier for me to answer questions about my problems than to lead the way
talkspace I think
i got to therapy and i don't even have any clinical mental health issues
"hstukenbourg is typing" -- i set myself up for that one did i
my therapist spotted adhd from across the room in a session, but didn't tell me until a little later
ADHD buddies! * high fives <@U3RJ9VDRT> *
wooo it screwed me over for years wooooo
wooo...

I suffer from depression and go to therapy and have for several years. My biggest issue is medication, which I’ve taken off and on over the years. I’m in an ‘off’ phase at the moment, but I recognize the difference this time and so am ramping up to get back onto it.

Talk therapy is very necessary part of the process, but recognize that for many (myself included) it isn’t enough by itself. I have to constant fight through my German upbringing about not viewing medication as a ‘crutch’.
what henry said
only irish catholic
Guilt and potatoes
we speak the same language
and soon, a gonti duel
It’s Guilt and Sausages for German catholics
anyways therapy has been a good experience for me. i think you should try it seth
You just have to find the right therapist
Don’t be afraid to “shop around”
The first one isn’t always the right one
worse case scenario, is the therapist and you figure out that you're not DM, Seth, or Kevin but like "Lord Huffinglust" or something
What Angelo mentioned is very true - it does take time to find someone who you feel you can trust and that you believe understands you.
Therapy is good for literally everyone, there shouldnt be any reason to shy away from it. Do it!

text: So..is it time to get into the separate the artist from the art discussion?
If you've made the moral adjustment to say it's ok to keep what you have, then it isn't a discussion.
So does it become morally ok to sell the cards to get money out of it then knowing it's still in circulation?
what if i sell it to a racist?
It's a moral question...no one can answer that but you.
Is it okay to buy collections from meth heads? Asking for a friend.
If you're able to come to terms with the idea of: "I know this person is a racist, abusive, dirtbag...but I really like X!" then that's where you've landed in the discussion.

Honestly, there's a degree of convenience to it. I can conveniently not give Orson Scott Card or Terese Nielsen any more of my money if given a chance to do so. But am I going to research anyone who does business with them and not do business with those businesses? No. I have a life to live, too.
brb getting chic fila
So I'm not gonna give her money for an autograph at MF Vegas. But I'm gonna give money to WotC.
might stop at hobby lobby on the way back to pick up some glitter

I don't think anyone's presenting that you need to exhaustively research your art, but if you discover it later, then you have to make a decision on how much does your like for the art overshadow your distaste for the artist and what they represent.
The Chic Fila thing is good example for another reason, in that they're just vocal about it, but it's not like 99% of massive corps don't also give money to the same shitty regressive causes.
Right, but in the case of Nielsen you have to eschew the entire company
Sure, but chances are very low that Chick Fil-A is the only place to eat around, so you're making a choice there.
Do I?
Does not playing her cards do anything?
It makes me feel better...it may not others, but that's why it's a moral question.
Chic fil a actively supports anti-queer lobbyists
Sure, CFA is actively worse than most
I'm just saying that it's hard to stop with being mad at just them and Hobby Lobby

I think WOTC is kind of an oddity for company in how entrenched their employees are with their audience. Like who do you tweet at for CFA? Anyone know a name and interact with them regularly? That's not the case with MTG and WOTC and even DnD. We KNOW a lot of those folks, some of us are even on friendly terms or are just friends with them, so it's easier for there to be a more emotional attachment to the issue

I'm strongly reminded of The Good Place right now.

"This Doug in 1782 got flowers for his grandmother, earned 72 points. But another Doug in 2017 got flowers for his grandma, same action, but LOST points because he ordered it on a cell phone made in a sweat shop, and the funds went to a CEO who sends unsolicited pictures of his genitals to his female employees."

"Also, there's this sandwich that if you eat it, it means you hate gay people. AND IT'S DELICIOUS."
WotC seems to actively pretending the Nielsen thing doesn't exist
Agreed, Dana
And i have a feeling if she was a lesser artist that wouldn't be the case

It also might be too soon for any of the changes they've made to be apparent by now considering how far into the future they work w/ this stuff. By the time the Nielsen stuff may have been coming to surface it was too late to make any changes to this set
Also agreed
Yeah, Matt, that's my thinking, too
But I don't know if most people will think of that, at least not at first
It's easier to have an emotional reaction first
Outside of "shit, we literally have to reprint this entire set because it's already done if so and it's not oging to fly w/ the higher ups to do that"
If we still see her stuff in a year+ then we might be able to say that. But if they have contracts w/ her for X cards left...
And let's be honest; Does anyone here think this will result in MH1 not selling well? Because I doubt that
They're making the same moral/business decision that any other company does
No, but I also don't think it would be fair to punish all of the other artists for her faults - this is too much of a collective and collaborative product to narrow it down to one person.
For sure.
Somewhere on the spectrum with Dana. If the artist is a bad person, wont get my card signed by them or be excited to see them. Am I boycotting the card? No.

For arguments sake as well, do we ever know when WOTC will take action?
In August we had it first pipe up from a random person. In April we had Terese tweet out her “letter.”

Depending on when WOTC pays attention changes a lot too. When do they start caring? That’s when the clock for activists starts.
Sets are locked around 6 months before release.
Maybe I'd feel different if I actually had a large care for an artist personally, but to me ... I really dont care about one of them having some backwards views.
and that's where you've come to terms with the morality of the discussion
If it wasnt for Twitter. I wouldn't even know of this persons existance. I cant get riled up over some Twitter drama and boycott a card over it
Discovering that a beloved artist hold or at least tolerates fairly reprehensible views on her fellow humans isn't a twitter drama
Yes, and its disappointing. However people going up in arms about the cards STILL is a bit silly in my eyes
Noted

And that's fairly my point about the Twitter comment. It seems alot of this comes from the twittersphere itself, maybe a little reddit. No one, from any walk of life goes on about these subjects to such an intensity for so long like Twitter
No one in rl*

And its werid comparing the Twitter life to my actual gameplay in real life with mtg overall... on a slightly separate subject.
Basically spending more time online absorbing an entirely different entity because of a hobby I spent a 100th of the time on in RL XD

The moral quandary of separating art from the artist is not a social media creation, but those platforms give us instant and persistent avenues to discuss in real time unlike in more social gatherings in RL.
Maybe not initially, but for these discussions to still be going on, you dont think it has anything to do with social media?
Social media has 'democratized' the debate to a wider audience who previously didn't have this question posed to them on a regular basis and in ways that reach the general consciousness.

Sorry, too me its always looked more like a platform for those to continously hop off one another to trade excessive outrage for likes. I think that eventually provides an unrealistic measure of what people truly think of the subject overall
And that's good thing in theory. But it also creates a moral minefield that is super hard to navigate.
A la the Good Place grandma flowers problem

And that's my issue. I have a very difficult time believing anyone on Twitter in general because of it. Only thing I can compare with is in RL... and no one cares all that much. On nearly any of the drama that doesnt actually pertain to bans/cards/etc
social media has shown the world that everyone underestimates how many other crazy people there are. that's not social media's fault or problem, it's humanity's.
To be fair, if I played with 99% white men neckbeards or that freemagic stuff... obvious why I dont. But I'm in Orlando. All walks of life. No one. I mean no one
TN and other controversies come up in my playgroup fairly often.
And I'm pretty sure I'm the only one on Twitter.
blaming social media for making people crazy is like blaming cell phone cameras for making cops shoot unarmed people.
they are technologies that show how fuxked up things actually have been all along
they don't create a new problem, they expose an existing one
Nate: not saying you're wrong, but I don't agree with the analogy.
Cell phones don't enable more people getting shot, they just make people aware of the occurrence.
Social media connects people with... opposing views that used to be isolated.
i didn't say cell phones enable more people getting shot?
But you're comparing that to social media.
social media makes people aware of the views of other people

What I'd like to see, just to see what happens, is TN go to a GP. 
I'd imagine that people would just skip the booth. Dont think there would be a riot or screaming or what have you
I'm just saying the comparison is... incompatible.
I'm with Nate on this. It increases awareness of what exists, but doesn't create more incidents.
I disagree wholeheartedly.
not sure what part you disagree with
I don't understand how.
I'd argue it creates it. Theres insentive for having opinions in the form of likes and follows
If someone held an opinion before social media, the fervor level of that opinion is fairly static.
Thing X is happening. News stations start reporting on Thing X so people know about it. Do you blame the news station for creating Thing X? They're just making you aware Thing X exists.
Its shaped my behavior once or twice. I'm assuming with others as well
Until they come across someone that moves it one way or the other.
Assuming that all news is accurate and created equal, how many people watch the news vs. use social media?
to start, that assumption is problematic
With the advent of social media, people that before didn't have access to others with similar or opposing views now have access to lots of people in both camps.
It was supposed to be.
I'm saying that the effect is exacerbated when news is misleading, biased, or wrong.
I'm not saying that becoming aware of Thing X doesn't change people behavior, I'm just saying that social media is not responsible for the existence of Thing X
All news has bias because it’s created by people. The idea that it was ever any other way is a nostalgic fantasy.
<@U3L7A68JC> yes, that's what I'm getting at.
Does that mean we should never do anything based on news, just because it holds bias and we interpret it with bias?
<@U3QMCLQQG> but it could make people aware of Thing X when they wouldn't have beforehand.
You’ve described the entire purpose of media
No, my only point was that the comparison itself was not applicable.
i still don't see where the disagreement is
Cell phones don't (necessarily) exacerbate police shootings.
Social media exacerbates people's viewpoints on subjects, one way or the other.
Especially when people get attacked.
I'll go with your qualifier: not necessarily
How many times has someone yelled at you on Twitter, and you thought afterward, "Boy, that tool on Twitter was right, I'll change my opinion"?
Now you're asking for anecdotal information
No, it was rhetorical.
I'm saying people don't respond to being attacked by changing their minds.
That premise supposes that all interactions on twitter are equivalent to folks screaming into the wind.
not ALL interaction on twitter is in the form of attacks.
Granted.
I'm oversimplifying for the sake of brevity.
I’ve certainly had reasoned discussion on Twitter on various topics that gave me pause.
I'd place you in the (possibly substantial) minority.
Dont think its screams in the wind. I DO think many post what they post for the full intent or at least subliminal intent of pushing their presence higher. That warps opinions
sometimes, reasonable discussions can be had between individuals, in the middle of an audience composed partially of trolls who can grab the microphone
But I agree with the qualifier: sometimes.
Again, I'm not disagreeing with the premise.
Just saying that, in the case of that specific analogy, cell phone recordings have a much smaller impact on police shootings than social media has on people's opinions.
you are saying that social media feeds on itself where cell phone evidence does not
... somewhat.
You know whats cool? Social media is half media itself.
I'm more speaking to the quantity (and perhaps quality) of impact, rather than whether the is any.
That's just science, can't disagree with that!
Science is a conspiracy of the liberal (social) media!
POE! POE! POE!
Science is a construct.
I could mostly agree with Nate's distillment of the point
[[metal worker]] is a construct
